<hl>
<seg id=1> France Opposed to Amending United Nations Charter </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> This paper, Paris, February 14, Telegram, Reporter Lu Wangda reports:  French Foreign Minister Dimas has indicated that France would not agree to a request to amend the United Nations charter by reassigning the five permanent seats on the Security Council. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> This announcement was made by the French foreign minister yesterday at a meeting of the Foreign Affairs Committee of the French National Assembly. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Foreign Minister Dimas feels that the United Nations was created after World War II, and that France, along with the other nations with permanent seats were all victorious countries. </seg>
<seg id=5> The defeated nations of Germany and Italy have already become democracies, but with regard to past events, is it enough just to glance back at history? </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> On this topic, there is a report that in today's economic powerhouses, Germany and Japan, there are people continuously requesting that the permanent seats on the United Nations Security Council be reassigned. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> German Foreign Minister Genshe issued a statement on the 11th expressing the hope that unified Germany would be able to have a greater effect on the United Nations and have a greater right to speak when decisions were made at the United Nations. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> The French foreign minister strongly indicated in response that these views were "unrealistic", that the permanent seats on the Security Council were provided for in the United Nations Charter, that amendment to the United Nations Charter requires unanimity of all member nations, and that France would not agree to amendment of the United Nations Charter. </seg>
</p>
